Consider the following grammar (that admits a series of declarations, followed by expressions) and the associated syntax directed translation (SDT) actions, given as pseudo-code:
P 🡪 D* E*
D 🡪 int ID {record that ID.lexeme is of type int}
D 🡪 bool ID {record that ID. lexeme is of type bool}
E 🡪 E _1 + E _2 {check that E _1 .type = E _2 .type = int; set E.type := int}
E 🡪 !E _1 {check that E _1 type = bool; set E.type = bool}
E 🡪 ID {set E.Type := int}
With respect to the above grammar, which one of the following choices is correct? [GATE 2021|| SET-1 MCQ|| 1-mark]

questions.explanation:
E → !E {If E _1 .type = int then E.type bool}
Note: Here instead of int, it is given as bool.
All actions can be used to type check syntactically correct integer variable declaration and integer expressions.

